  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(42) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "The fear of Isaac",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—That is, the object of Isaac’s worship. The reason given by the Jewish Commentators for this remarkable way of describing the Deity whom Isaac served is that, as his father was still alive, Jacob would have been wanting in reverence, if he had spoken of God as “Isaac’s God,” even though Jehovah had condescended so to call Himself (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 28:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Genesis 31:42",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Genesis 31:42",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Except God had been with me — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Jacob, on every mention of his substance, attributes all the increase of it to the care that God had of him. And he here speaks of God, as the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "God of his father, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "intimating, that he thought himself unworthy to be thus regarded, but was ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "beloved for his father’s sake. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "He calls him the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "God of Abraham ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the Fear of Isaac: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "for Abraham was dead, and gone to that world where there is no fear; but Isaac was yet alive, sanctifying the Lord in his heart ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "as his fear and his dread.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
